00:24:47,028 --> 00:24:48,460
What'd he say?

260
00:24:48,528 --> 00:24:49,961
What'd he say?

261
00:24:50,030 --> 00:24:52,965
"Look, I washed
for supper."

262
00:24:53,034 --> 00:24:54,501
Ha ha ha ha!

263
00:25:05,780 --> 00:25:06,712
Hey, Fish.

264
00:25:06,781 --> 00:25:07,712
Yeah?

265
00:25:07,781 --> 00:25:09,476
Look at this.
A Hitler Youth knife.

266
00:25:11,551 --> 00:25:13,986
And now it's a shabbat
challah cutter, right?

267
00:25:18,059 --> 00:25:19,720
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(GROANS)</font></b>

268
00:25:24,198 --> 00:25:25,665
<b><font color="#404040">SOLDIER:</font></b>
Keep it moving!

269
00:25:42,583 --> 00:25:44,414
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(SOBBING)</font></b>

270
00:26:26,626 --> 00:26:28,219
<b><font color="#404040">HORVATH:</font></b>
That's quite a view.

271
00:26:29,463 --> 00:26:30,896
Yes, it is.

272
00:26:32,633 --> 00:26:34,066
Quite a view.

273
00:27:57,518 --> 00:27:59,452
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(TYPEWRITERS CLACKING)</font></b>

274
00:28:08,896 --> 00:28:11,160
<b><font color="#404040">MAN'S VOICE:</font></b>
"Dear Mr. Brian Boyd,

275
00:28:11,232 --> 00:28:12,995
no doubt by now you have
received full information..."

276
00:28:13,067 --> 00:28:14,261
<b><font color="#404040">SECOND MAN:</font></b>
"Dear Mrs. Jensen..."

277
00:28:14,335 --> 00:28:15,825
"...about the untimely
death of your son."

278
00:28:15,903 --> 00:28:17,666
"...no words of mine can
ever relieve the grief..."

279
00:28:17,738 --> 00:28:20,171
<b><font color="#404040">THIRD MAN:</font></b> "Our outfit has
felt his loss tremendously."

280
00:28:20,240 --> 00:28:21,674
<b><font color="#404040">FOURTH MAN:</font></b>
"He was a fine soldier,

281
00:28:21,742 --> 00:28:23,175
and he believed
very strongly in..."

282
00:28:23,244 --> 00:28:24,677
<b><font color="#404040">FIFTH MAN:</font></b>
"It's no secret anymore...

283
00:28:24,745 --> 00:28:26,178
that we were involved

284
00:28:26,247 --> 00:28:28,181
in one of the most important
operations of this war."

285
00:28:28,249 --> 00:28:30,183
<b><font color="#404040">FIRST MAN:</font></b> "Al was the one
who held us all together.

286
00:28:30,251 --> 00:28:31,843
he was always the first to
volunteer and the last..."

287
00:28:31,919 --> 00:28:33,682
<b><font color="#404040">SIXTH MAN:</font></b> "...came to
a clearing near a road

288
00:28:33,754 --> 00:28:35,517
where over 4,000 troops
had passed."

289
00:28:35,589 --> 00:28:37,682
<b><font color="#404040">SEVENTH MAN:</font></b> "Your husband
served in a combat unit

290
00:28:37,758 --> 00:28:40,693
whose dangerous duty is
to place itself beyond..."

291
00:28:40,761 --> 00:28:43,696
<b><font color="#404040">EIGHTH MAN:</font></b> "...which we all
cherish and hold so dear.

292
00:28:43,764 --> 00:28:46,028
The loss of Lee
and others like him

293
00:28:46,100 --> 00:28:47,692
is a distinct blow
to the regiment."

294
00:28:47,768 --> 00:28:49,201
<b><font color="#404040">NINTH MAN:</font></b> "I fully
understand your desire

295
00:28:49,270 --> 00:28:52,205
to learn as much as possible
regarding the circumstances

296
00:28:52,273 --> 00:28:53,706
leading to his death."

297
00:28:53,774 --> 00:28:55,298
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(VOICES FADE)</font></b>

298
00:29:17,297 --> 00:29:19,232
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(CONVERSATION INAUDIBLE)</font></b>

299
00:29:46,227 --> 00:29:47,751
Colonel, I've got something
you should know about.

300
00:29:47,828 --> 00:29:48,920
Yes?

301
00:29:50,831 --> 00:29:54,267
These 2 men died in Normandy.

302
00:29:54,335 --> 00:29:56,269
This one at Omaha Beach.

303
00:29:57,338 --> 00:29:58,669
"Sean Ryan."

304
00:29:58,739 --> 00:30:00,764
This man at Utah.

305
00:30:02,343 --> 00:30:03,833
"Peter Ryan."

306
00:30:07,681 --> 00:30:10,616
This man was killed
last week in New Guinea.

307
00:30:13,320 --> 00:30:14,753
"Daniel...

308
00:30:14,822 --> 00:30:16,153
Ryan."

309
00:30:16,223 --> 00:30:18,157
The 3 men are brothers, sir.

310
00:30:18,225 --> 00:30:20,159
I've just learned
that this afternoon

311
00:30:20,227 --> 00:30:22,593
their mother's going to be
getting all 3 telegrams.

312
00:30:26,834 --> 00:30:28,267
That's not all.

313
00:30:28,335 --> 00:30:30,098
There's a fourth brother,
the youngest.

314
00:30:30,171 --> 00:30:31,604
He parachuted in
with the 101st Airborne

315
00:30:31,672 --> 00:30:33,106
night before the invasion.

316
00:30:33,175 --> 00:30:34,766
He's somewhere in Normandy.
We don't know where.

317
00:30:34,842 --> 00:30:36,104
Is he alive?

318
00:30:36,177 --> 00:30:37,610
We don't know.

319
00:30:41,182 --> 00:30:42,376
Come with me.

320
00:32:26,621 --> 00:32:29,783
<b><font color="#404040">GENERAL MARSHALL:</font></b>
Goddamn it.

321
00:32:29,857 --> 00:32:32,325
All 4 of them were
in the same company

322
00:32:32,393 --> 00:32:33,951
in the 29th Division,

323
00:32:34,028 --> 00:32:35,495
but we split them up

324
00:32:35,563 --> 00:32:36,996
after the Sullivan brothers
died on the Juneau.

325
00:32:37,064 --> 00:32:39,498
Well, any, uh, contact
with the fourth son, James?

326
00:32:39,567 --> 00:32:40,499
No, sir.

327
00:32:40,568 --> 00:32:42,502
He was dropped
about 15 miles inland

328
00:32:42,570 --> 00:32:44,003
near Neuville.

329
00:32:44,071 --> 00:32:46,006
But that's still deep
behind German lines.

330
00:32:46,074 --> 00:32:48,007
Now, Mac, there is
no way you can know

331
00:32:48,075 --> 00:32:50,009
where in the hell
he was dropped.

332
00:32:50,077 --> 00:32:52,170
First reports out of
lke's people at Shaef

333
00:32:52,246 --> 00:32:54,510
said the 101st is scattered
all to hell and gone.

334
00:32:54,582 --> 00:32:56,516
There's misdrops
all over Normandy.

335
00:32:56,584 --> 00:32:59,849
Assuming Private Ryan
even survived the jump,

336
00:32:59,920 --> 00:33:01,353
he could be anywhere.

337
00:33:01,422 --> 00:33:03,014
In fact,
he's probably K.I.A.

338
00:33:03,090 --> 00:33:04,524
And frankly, sir,

339
00:33:04,593 --> 00:33:07,026
we go sending some sort
of rescue mission,

340
00:33:07,094 --> 00:33:09,688
flat-hatting through swarms
of German reinforcements

341
00:33:09,763 --> 00:33:11,526
all along our axis
of advance,

342
00:33:11,599 --> 00:33:13,362
they're gonna be K.I.A. too.

343
00:33:36,624 --> 00:33:38,057
I have a letter here...

344
00:33:39,793 --> 00:33:44,060
written a long time ago
to a Mrs. Bixby in Boston.

345
00:33:44,132 --> 00:33:46,224
So bear with me.

346
00:33:48,802 --> 00:33:50,269
"Dear Madam,

347
00:33:50,337 --> 00:33:53,397
I have been shown in the files
of the war department

348
00:33:53,474 --> 00:33:57,570
a statement of the adjutant
general of Massachusetts

349
00:33:57,645 --> 00:33:59,078
that you...

350
00:33:59,146 --> 00:34:01,081
are the mother of 5...

351
00:34:03,084 --> 00:34:06,575
sons who have died gloriously
on the field of battle.

352
00:34:09,657 --> 00:34:13,423
I feel how weak and fruitless
must be any words of mine...

353
00:34:14,828 --> 00:34:17,922
that would attempt
to beguile you from the grief...

354
00:34:17,998 --> 00:34:20,763
of a loss so overwhelming.

355
00:34:22,170 --> 00:34:24,603
But I cannot refrain
from tendering to you

356
00:34:24,672 --> 00:34:27,106
the consolation
that may be found...

357
00:34:28,175 --> 00:34:30,109
in the thanks
of the republic...

358
00:34:31,178 --> 00:34:32,611
they died to save.

359
00:34:36,183 --> 00:34:38,117
I pray that
Our Heavenly Father

360
00:34:38,185 --> 00:34:40,950
may assuage the anguish
of your bereavement

361
00:34:41,022 --> 00:34:42,955
and leave you only
the cherished memory

362
00:34:43,023 --> 00:34:45,355
of the loved and lost...

363
00:34:46,527 --> 00:34:48,620
and the solemn pride
that must be yours

364
00:34:48,696 --> 00:34:50,630
to have laid so costly
a sacrifice

365
00:34:50,698 --> 00:34:52,632
upon the altar of freedom.

366
00:34:52,700 --> 00:34:55,134
Yours very sincerely
and respectfully...

367
00:34:56,203 --> 00:34:57,637
''Abraham Lincoln."

368
00:35:17,058 --> 00:35:18,821
That boy is alive.

369
00:35:19,961 --> 00:35:22,485
We are gonna send somebody
to find him...

370
00:35:23,731 --> 00:35:26,666
and we are gonna get him
the hell out of there.

371
00:35:27,735 --> 00:35:29,726
- Yes, sir.
- Yes, sir.

372
00:35:42,082 --> 00:35:43,515
We expected 32 tanks
on the beach.

373
00:35:43,584 --> 00:35:44,676
27 didn't make it.

374
00:35:44,752 --> 00:35:46,014
Miller, Charlie Company.

375
00:35:46,086 --> 00:35:47,178
Go on in, Captain.

376
00:35:47,254 --> 00:35:48,687
I understand
your situation,

377
00:35:48,756 --> 00:35:51,190
but if we don't off-load
those Shermans by 0600,

378
00:35:51,258 --> 00:35:53,021
we're gonna have
an entire division

379
00:35:53,093 --> 00:35:56,029
stuck at Carentan with
its pants around its ankles.

380
00:35:56,097 --> 00:35:58,031
Well, you let me know.

381
00:35:58,099 --> 00:36:00,032
Have Charlie Company
hold at Vierville

382
00:36:00,100 --> 00:36:02,193
until we can get
some armor up there.

383
00:36:02,269 --> 00:36:04,032
Yes, sir.
Runner!

384
00:36:04,104 --> 00:36:07,005
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(TRUCK IGNITION GRINDING)</font></b>

385
00:36:09,843 --> 00:36:11,538
Airborne was supposed
to win an open door

386
00:36:11,612 --> 00:36:13,046
for the rest of us.

387
00:36:13,114 --> 00:36:14,206
Instead they misdropped,

388
00:36:14,282 --> 00:36:15,715
scattered all their
sticks into the wind.

389
00:36:15,784 --> 00:36:16,876
What's your situation?

390
00:36:16,951 --> 00:36:19,544
Uh, yes, sir.
Sector 4 is secure.

391
00:36:19,620 --> 00:36:21,554
We, uh...

392
00:36:21,622 --> 00:36:23,954
we took out towed 88s

393
00:36:24,024 --> 00:36:26,049
here, here...

394
00:36:26,126 --> 00:36:27,218
and here.

395
00:36:27,294 --> 00:36:29,057
They'd already gotten
4 of our Shermans

396
00:36:29,129 --> 00:36:30,562
and a number of our
deuce-and-a-halves.

397
00:36:30,631 --> 00:36:33,066
These 2 minefields
are actually one big one.

398
00:36:33,134 --> 00:36:35,068
We tried to make our way up
through the middle of it,

399
00:36:35,136 --> 00:36:37,569
but it turned into a mixed,
high-density field--

400
00:36:37,638 --> 00:36:39,071
little bit of everything.

401
00:36:39,139 --> 00:36:40,731
Sprengmine 44s,
Schumine 42s,

402
00:36:40,808 --> 00:36:43,072
pot mines, A-200s--
the little wooden bastards

403
00:36:43,143 --> 00:36:46,078
that the mine detectors
don't pick up.

404
00:36:46,146 --> 00:36:48,080
This road here...

405
00:36:48,148 --> 00:36:50,082
they placed big mushrooms--
Teller mine 43s,

406
00:36:50,150 --> 00:36:51,743
I guess for our tanks--

407
00:36:51,820 --> 00:36:54,254
from here right up
to the edge of the village,

408
00:36:54,322 --> 00:36:55,584
right here.

409
00:36:55,657 --> 00:36:57,590
So we marked 'em,
called the engineers.

410
00:36:57,658 --> 00:36:58,920
Resistance?

411
00:36:58,992 --> 00:37:01,085
We had higher support
expectations, sir.

412
00:37:01,161 --> 00:37:03,595
There was an understrength
company without artillery.

413
00:37:03,664 --> 00:37:07,100
Wehrmacht 346 Infantry,
Von Luck Kampfgruppe.

414
00:37:07,167 --> 00:37:08,930
We ended up
with 23 prisoners.

415
00:37:09,002 --> 00:37:11,267
We turned them over
to M.P.s from the 29th.

416
00:37:15,009 --> 00:37:16,942
What about our casualties?

417
00:37:18,011 --> 00:37:19,308
Well...

418
00:37:19,379 --> 00:37:21,108
the figures...

419
00:37:21,181 --> 00:37:23,615
were 35 dead...

420
00:37:23,684 --> 00:37:24,946
times 2 wounded.

421
00:37:25,018 --> 00:37:26,451
They just...

422
00:37:26,520 --> 00:37:28,785
didn't wanna give up
those 88s.

423
00:37:30,191 --> 00:37:33,126
It was a tough assignment.
That's why you got it.

424
00:37:33,194 --> 00:37:34,627
Yes, sir.

425
00:37:35,863 --> 00:37:37,125
John...

426
00:37:40,367 --> 00:37:41,959
I've got another one
for you.

427
00:37:42,035 --> 00:37:43,127
Yes, sir.

428
00:37:43,203 --> 00:37:45,398
This one's straight
from the top.

429
00:37:50,078 --> 00:37:51,511
<b><font color="#404040">MILLER:</font></b>
I wish.

430
00:37:51,579 --> 00:37:53,672
You and I are taking
a squad over to Neuville

431
00:37:53,748 --> 00:37:56,011
on a public relations mission.

432
00:37:56,083 --> 00:37:58,017
<b><font color="#404040">HORVATH:</font></b>
You leading a squad?

433
00:37:58,085 --> 00:38:01,179
Some private in the 101st
lost 3 brothers,

434
00:38:01,255 --> 00:38:02,847
and he's got a ticket home.

435
00:38:02,923 --> 00:38:04,356
How come Neuville?

436
00:38:04,424 --> 00:38:06,016
They think he's up there
somewhere,

437
00:38:06,093 --> 00:38:08,028
part of all
those airborne misdrops.

438
00:38:08,096 --> 00:38:09,529
It's not gonna be easy

439
00:38:09,597 --> 00:38:11,030
finding one
particular soldier

440
00:38:11,099 --> 00:38:12,532
in the middle of this
whole goddamn war.

441
00:38:12,600 --> 00:38:14,533
Like finding a needle
in a stack of needles.

442
00:38:14,601 --> 00:38:16,193
But what about
the company?

443
00:38:16,270 --> 00:38:18,033
We take the pick
of the litter,

444
00:38:18,105 --> 00:38:20,039
and the rest get folded
into Baker.

445
00:38:20,107 --> 00:38:21,540
Jesus Christ.

446
00:38:21,608 --> 00:38:23,872
They took away
your company?

447
00:38:23,944 --> 00:38:26,209
It wasn't my company,
it was the army's.

448
00:38:26,281 --> 00:38:28,215
So they told me, anyway.

449
00:38:28,283 --> 00:38:29,716
Give me REIBEN on B.A.R.,

450
00:38:29,784 --> 00:38:32,048
JACKSON, WADE, Beasley
and Caparzo.

451
00:38:32,120 --> 00:38:33,711
Beasley's dead.

452
00:38:33,787 --> 00:38:35,379
All right.
MELLISH then.

453
00:38:35,455 --> 00:38:36,888
We got anybody speaks French?

454
00:38:36,957 --> 00:38:38,549
Not that I know of.

455
00:38:39,626 --> 00:38:40,888
What about Talbot?

456
00:38:40,961 --> 00:38:41,893
This morning.

457
00:38:41,962 --> 00:38:42,894
Oh.

458
00:38:42,963 --> 00:38:44,055
All right.

459
00:38:44,131 --> 00:38:46,066
I'm gonna go try to dig up
another interpreter.

460
00:38:46,134 --> 00:38:48,568
Assemble at Battalion
Motor Pool on the beach.

461
00:38:48,636 --> 00:38:49,568
Yes, sir.

462
00:38:49,637 --> 00:38:51,070
What are we gonna do?

463
00:38:51,139 --> 00:38:52,070
Listen up-- What?

464
00:38:52,139 --> 00:38:53,231
What we gonna do?

465
00:38:53,307 --> 00:38:54,740
You're going home wrapped
in an American flag

466
00:38:54,808 --> 00:38:56,400
with a hunk of cheese
in your ass, Caparzo.

467
00:38:56,476 --> 00:38:58,410
I thought you liked it
in the ass.

468
00:38:58,478 --> 00:38:59,604
What?

469
00:38:59,680 --> 00:39:01,648
Attention!

470
00:39:01,715 --> 00:39:03,149
As you were.

471
00:39:03,217 --> 00:39:04,980
I'm looking
for Corporal Upham...

472
00:39:05,053 --> 00:39:05,985
Timothy E.

473
00:39:06,054 --> 00:39:07,043
I'm Upham, sir.

474
00:39:07,121 --> 00:39:08,816
I understand you speak
French and German.

475
00:39:08,890 --> 00:39:09,822
Yes, sir.

476
00:39:09,891 --> 00:39:10,982
How's your accent?

477
00:39:11,058 --> 00:39:12,491
Just a slight one
in French,

478
00:39:12,559 --> 00:39:13,992
but my German's clean.
A touch of Bavarian, sir.

479
00:39:14,061 --> 00:39:15,494
Very good. You've
been reassigned to me.

480
00:39:15,562 --> 00:39:16,654
Grab your gear.

481
00:39:16,730 --> 00:39:17,924
We're going to a place
called Neuville.

482
00:39:17,998 --> 00:39:18,930
Yes, sir.

483
00:39:18,999 --> 00:39:20,057
When was this updated?

484
00:39:20,133 --> 00:39:21,498
Updated as of 0830
this morning.

485
00:39:21,568 --> 00:39:22,593
Uh, sir...

486
00:39:22,670 --> 00:39:24,160
this is
the 12th S.S. Panzer.

487
00:39:24,238 --> 00:39:26,001
These are the 2 axis
that advance south.

488
00:39:26,074 --> 00:39:27,507
Sir, there are Germans
in Neuville.

489
00:39:27,575 --> 00:39:29,008
That's what I understand,
Corporal.

490
00:39:29,077 --> 00:39:30,509
Um, sir,

491
00:39:30,577 --> 00:39:32,511
there are a lot of Germans
in Neuville.

492
00:39:32,579 --> 00:39:34,012
You have a problem
with that, Corporal?

493
00:39:34,081 --> 00:39:35,173
No, sir.

494
00:39:35,248 --> 00:39:37,011
Just if you consider
I've never been in combat.

495
00:39:37,084 --> 00:39:38,517
I make maps,
and I translate.

496
00:39:38,585 --> 00:39:40,519
I need someone who speaks
French and German.

497
00:39:40,587 --> 00:39:41,520
Yes, sir.

498
00:39:41,589 --> 00:39:43,022
My 2 guys were killed.

499
00:39:43,091 --> 00:39:44,524
It's just that
I haven't held a weapon

500
00:39:44,592 --> 00:39:46,025
since basic training, sir.

501
00:39:46,094 --> 00:39:48,028
Did you fire the weapon
in basic training?

502
00:39:48,096 --> 00:39:49,187
Yes, sir.

503
00:39:49,262 --> 00:39:51,025
Well, then get your gear.

504
00:39:51,098 --> 00:39:52,030
Yes, sir.

505
00:39:53,100 --> 00:39:54,431
Sir, may I br--

506
00:39:59,106 --> 00:40:01,041
May I bring
my typewriter, sir?

507
00:40:06,247 --> 00:40:08,044
Yes, sir.

508
00:40:11,118 --> 00:40:13,052
Thank you very much, sir.

509
00:40:13,120 --> 00:40:14,553
That a souvenir?

510
00:40:14,621 --> 00:40:15,883
Uh, no, sir.

511
00:40:15,956 --> 00:40:17,719
Take your time, Corporal.

512
