- You think?
- Yeah.

1008
01:03:06,193 --> 01:03:08,956
Ryan? Don't know-- Man!

1009
01:03:09,028 --> 01:03:11,326
<b><font color="#404040">MILLER:</font></b> Where was
your drop zone?

1010
01:03:11,398 --> 01:03:12,763
Just inside of Vierville.

1011
01:03:12,832 --> 01:03:13,890
Vierville?

1012
01:03:13,967 --> 01:03:15,696
How the hell did you
end up way up here?

1013
01:03:15,769 --> 01:03:17,031
You got me, sir.

1014
01:03:17,103 --> 01:03:19,038
C-47 took heavy fire.

1015
01:03:19,106 --> 01:03:20,767
Pilot went crazy trying
to get out of there,

1016
01:03:20,841 --> 01:03:22,103
turning every which way,

1017
01:03:22,176 --> 01:03:24,542
took more fire in the drop,
got messy.

1018
01:03:24,612 --> 01:03:26,011
I ended up here.

1019
01:03:26,080 --> 01:03:28,138
I haven't seen a single guy
from my stick, sir.

1020
01:03:28,214 --> 01:03:29,545
God knows
where they are.

1021
01:03:29,616 --> 01:03:31,311
Anybody from Baker Company
have a big mouth?

1022
01:03:31,384 --> 01:03:33,284
Say where the drop zone
might've been?

1023
01:03:33,353 --> 01:03:35,150
No, sir,
but I know Baker Company

1024
01:03:35,221 --> 01:03:36,814
had the same rally point
as us.

1025
01:03:36,891 --> 01:03:38,859
Show me.

1026
01:03:38,926 --> 01:03:40,393
My men are beat.

1027
01:03:40,461 --> 01:03:42,395
We're gonna hold up here
for about 3 hours.

1028
01:03:42,463 --> 01:03:44,624
We'll pull out after dark.

1029
01:03:44,698 --> 01:03:46,632
Got anything left
in this town

1030
01:03:46,699 --> 01:03:49,099
like a 3-star hotel,
something with clean sheets

1031
01:03:49,169 --> 01:03:51,569
and soft pillows
and room service?

1032
01:03:51,638 --> 01:03:53,572
How about
a nice comfy church?

1033
01:03:53,640 --> 01:03:54,572
We'll take that.

1034
01:03:54,641 --> 01:03:55,904
What have you heard?

1035
01:03:55,976 --> 01:03:57,568
How's it all
falling together?

1036
01:03:57,645 --> 01:03:59,545
Well, we got
the beachhead secure.

1037
01:03:59,613 --> 01:04:02,377
Problem is Monty's taking
his time moving on Caen.

1038
01:04:02,450 --> 01:04:04,941
We can't pull out
till he's ready. So--

1039
01:04:05,019 --> 01:04:06,349
That guy's overrated.

1040
01:04:06,419 --> 01:04:07,511
No argument here.

1041
01:04:07,587 --> 01:04:10,351
You got to take Caen,
so you can take Saint-Lo.

1042
01:04:10,423 --> 01:04:12,323
You got to take Saint-Lo
to take Valognes.

1043
01:04:12,392 --> 01:04:13,950
Valognes,
you got Cherbourg.

1044
01:04:14,027 --> 01:04:15,586
And Cherbourg,
you got Paris.

1045
01:04:15,663 --> 01:04:17,893
Paris, you get Berlin.

1046
01:04:17,965 --> 01:04:19,956
And then
that big boat home.

1047
01:04:22,269 --> 01:04:25,237
We sure as hell could
use you around here,

1048
01:04:25,305 --> 01:04:27,239
but I understand
what you're doing.

1049
01:04:27,307 --> 01:04:28,399
You do?

1050
01:04:28,475 --> 01:04:31,603
Yeah. I got a couple
of brothers myself.

1051
01:04:31,678 --> 01:04:32,645
Oh.

1052
01:04:32,712 --> 01:04:34,146
Good luck.

1053
01:04:34,215 --> 01:04:35,341
Thank you.

1054
01:04:35,416 --> 01:04:36,940
No, I mean it.

1055
01:04:37,017 --> 01:04:39,611
Find him.
Get him home.

1056
01:04:47,827 --> 01:04:50,125
<b><font color="#404040">HORVATH:</font></b>
What's with your hand?

1057
01:04:50,196 --> 01:04:52,495
I don't know.

1058
01:04:54,134 --> 01:04:55,396
It started in Portsmouth

1059
01:04:55,469 --> 01:04:57,994
when they brought us
down for embarkation.

1060
01:04:58,072 --> 01:04:59,505
It comes and goes.

1061
01:04:59,573 --> 01:05:02,701
Well, you may have to get
yourself a new line of work.

1062
01:05:02,776 --> 01:05:05,710
This one doesn't seem
to agree with you anymore.

1063
01:05:11,185 --> 01:05:12,447
What?

1064
01:05:16,524 --> 01:05:17,491
What?

1065
01:05:17,558 --> 01:05:18,547
Nothing.

1066
01:05:18,626 --> 01:05:21,561
What was the name
of that kid at Anzio?

1067
01:05:21,629 --> 01:05:23,220
The one that was always

1068
01:05:23,296 --> 01:05:24,820
walking around
on his hands, you know,

1069
01:05:24,898 --> 01:05:26,866
and he was
singing that song

1070
01:05:26,933 --> 01:05:28,594
about the man
on the flying trapeze?

1071
01:05:28,668 --> 01:05:29,657
Vecchio.

1072
01:05:29,736 --> 01:05:31,261
Vecchio.

1073
01:05:34,675 --> 01:05:36,734
Yeah.

1074
01:05:36,810 --> 01:05:38,277
Yeah, Vecchio.

1075
01:05:38,345 --> 01:05:40,745
He was a goofy kid.

1076
01:05:40,814 --> 01:05:44,943
I remember he used to pee
a "V" on everybody's jacket

1077
01:05:45,018 --> 01:05:47,213
for Vecchio.

1078
01:05:47,287 --> 01:05:48,584
For victory.

1079
01:05:48,655 --> 01:05:49,884
Vecchio.

1080
01:05:52,793 --> 01:05:54,260
He was so short.

1081
01:05:54,328 --> 01:05:56,262
He was a midget,
wasn't he?

1082
01:05:56,330 --> 01:05:58,195
"How did you
get to be a ranger?"

1083
01:05:58,265 --> 01:05:59,527
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(BOTH CHUCKLING)</font></b>

1084
01:05:59,600 --> 01:06:01,829
He got shot in the foot once,
didn't he?

1085
01:06:01,901 --> 01:06:03,334
And he was walking
on his hands.

1086
01:06:03,403 --> 01:06:05,598
Yeah, well, he could
walk faster on his hands.

1087
01:06:07,574 --> 01:06:10,203
He could run faster
on his hands than...

1088
01:06:13,314 --> 01:06:15,544
Vecchio.

1089
01:06:15,616 --> 01:06:17,049
Yeah.

1090
01:06:18,586 --> 01:06:20,052
Caparzo.

1091
01:06:26,092 --> 01:06:27,355
You see, when...

1092
01:06:29,530 --> 01:06:32,522
when you end up killing
one of your men, you see,

1093
01:06:32,600 --> 01:06:35,694
you tell yourself
it happened

1094
01:06:35,769 --> 01:06:39,864
so you could save
the lives of 2 or 3

1095
01:06:39,939 --> 01:06:42,874
or 10 others.

1096
01:06:42,942 --> 01:06:45,035
Maybe a hundred others.

1097
01:06:49,083 --> 01:06:52,314
Do you know how many men
I've lost under my command?

1098
01:06:52,386 --> 01:06:53,318
How many?

1099
01:06:53,387 --> 01:06:55,651
94.

1100
01:06:55,723 --> 01:06:59,419
But that means
I've saved the lives

1101
01:06:59,492 --> 01:07:01,722
of 10 times that many,
doesn't it?

1102
01:07:01,794 --> 01:07:04,787
Maybe even 20, right?

1103
01:07:04,865 --> 01:07:06,298
20 times as many?

1104
01:07:11,972 --> 01:07:14,304
And that's
how simple it is.

1105
01:07:15,376 --> 01:07:17,570
That's how you...

1106
01:07:17,644 --> 01:07:18,838
That's how you

1107
01:07:18,911 --> 01:07:20,776
rationalize
making the choice

1108
01:07:20,847 --> 01:07:23,976
between the mission
and the men.

1109
01:07:24,051 --> 01:07:26,986
Except this time,
this mission is a man.

1110
01:07:30,391 --> 01:07:32,757
This Ryan
better be worth it.

1111
01:07:35,829 --> 01:07:38,763
He'd better go home
and cure some disease

1112
01:07:38,831 --> 01:07:42,962
or invent a longer-lasting
lightbulb or something.

1113
01:07:43,037 --> 01:07:44,834
'Cause the truth is,
I wouldn't trade 10 Ryans

1114
01:07:44,905 --> 01:07:47,738
for one Vecchio
or one Caparzo.

1115
01:07:47,808 --> 01:07:49,776
Amen.

1116
01:07:49,843 --> 01:07:50,810
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(GRUNTS)</font></b>

1117
01:07:50,878 --> 01:07:53,904
Look.
There it goes again.

1118
01:07:53,981 --> 01:07:55,414
Sir...

1119
01:07:55,482 --> 01:07:58,450
are you all right?

1120
01:08:02,856 --> 01:08:05,791
Now, look, we're gonna
move out in 2 hours.

1121
01:08:05,859 --> 01:08:07,724
Why don't you
get some sleep?

1122
01:08:07,795 --> 01:08:10,525
<b><font color="#404040">REIBEN:</font></b> I don't know
how he does it.

1123
01:08:10,597 --> 01:08:11,689
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b> What's that?

1124
01:08:11,765 --> 01:08:13,027
Falls asleep like that.

1125
01:08:13,100 --> 01:08:14,431
I mean, look at him.

1126
01:08:14,501 --> 01:08:17,594
The guy's lights out the minute
his head hits the pack.

1127
01:08:17,670 --> 01:08:19,001
Clear conscience.

1128
01:08:19,072 --> 01:08:21,667
Yeah, what's that saying?
"If God's on our side,

1129
01:08:21,742 --> 01:08:23,676
who the hell could
be on theirs?"

1130
01:08:23,744 --> 01:08:26,941
"If God be for us,
who could be against us?"

1131
01:08:27,014 --> 01:08:28,504
Yeah, what did I say?

1132
01:08:28,582 --> 01:08:29,742
<b><font color="#404040">WADE:</font></b> Well, actually,

1133
01:08:29,817 --> 01:08:33,514
the trick to falling asleep
is trying to stay awake.

1134
01:08:33,587 --> 01:08:35,486
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b>
How is that, WADE?

1135
01:08:35,555 --> 01:08:37,352
<b><font color="#404040">WADE:</font></b> Well, when my
mother was an intern,

1136
01:08:37,423 --> 01:08:40,587
she used to work late
through the night,

1137
01:08:40,661 --> 01:08:42,185
sleep through the day.

1138
01:08:42,262 --> 01:08:43,627
So the only time

1139
01:08:43,697 --> 01:08:44,925
that we ever got
to talk about anything

1140
01:08:44,998 --> 01:08:46,488
was when she'd get home.

1141
01:08:46,567 --> 01:08:49,161
So what I used to do,
I used to lie in my bed

1142
01:08:49,236 --> 01:08:50,601
and try to stay awake
as long as I could,

1143
01:08:50,671 --> 01:08:54,606
but it never worked
'cause the harder I tried,

1144
01:08:54,674 --> 01:08:56,505
the faster
I'd fall asleep.

1145
01:08:56,576 --> 01:08:59,842
Yeah, well, that wouldn't have
mattered none in my house.

1146
01:08:59,913 --> 01:09:02,279
My ma, she would've come home,
shook me awake,

1147
01:09:02,349 --> 01:09:04,874
chatted me up till dawn.

1148
01:09:04,952 --> 01:09:07,147
I swear, that woman
was never too tired to talk.

1149
01:09:07,221 --> 01:09:09,155
Yeah, that's probably
the only time

1150
01:09:09,223 --> 01:09:12,090
she could get a word in.

1151
01:09:13,793 --> 01:09:15,590
Funny thing is,

1152
01:09:15,661 --> 01:09:18,756
sometimes she'd
come home early,

1153
01:09:18,832 --> 01:09:21,323
and I'd pretend
to be asleep.

1154
01:09:21,401 --> 01:09:24,199
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b> Who?
Your-- Your mom?

1155
01:09:24,271 --> 01:09:25,363
Yeah.

1156
01:09:27,341 --> 01:09:29,969
She'd stand in the doorway
looking at me.

1157
01:09:31,478 --> 01:09:34,071
And I would just
keep my eyes shut.

1158
01:09:36,383 --> 01:09:40,410
And I knew she just wanted
to find out about my day,

1159
01:09:40,487 --> 01:09:42,284
that she came home early...

1160
01:09:44,591 --> 01:09:47,355
just to talk to me.

1161
01:09:49,163 --> 01:09:50,755
And I still wouldn't move.

1162
01:09:50,830 --> 01:09:53,390
I'd still pretend
to just be asleep.

1163
01:10:01,041 --> 01:10:03,305
I don't know why I did that.

1164
01:10:16,857 --> 01:10:18,188
<b><font color="#404040">MILLER:</font></b>
We only got a couple hours.

1165
01:10:18,258 --> 01:10:20,192
Shut up and go to sleep.

1166
01:10:29,268 --> 01:10:30,929
Captain?

1167
01:10:31,003 --> 01:10:32,733
<b><font color="#404040">UPHAM:</font></b> Sir?

1168
01:10:34,274 --> 01:10:35,605
Corporal?

1169
01:10:40,414 --> 01:10:43,281
How you doin' there?
You all right?

1170
01:10:43,350 --> 01:10:48,480
Yeah, I think this is
all good for me, sir.

1171
01:10:48,554 --> 01:10:50,852
Really?

1172
01:10:50,923 --> 01:10:52,084
How is that?

1173
01:10:56,096 --> 01:10:58,826
"War educates
the senses,

1174
01:10:58,899 --> 01:11:00,890
calls into action
the will,

1175
01:11:00,968 --> 01:11:04,062
perfects the physical
constitution,

1176
01:11:04,137 --> 01:11:07,072
brings men into such
swift and close collision

1177
01:11:07,140 --> 01:11:10,576
in critical moments
that man measures man."

1178
01:11:10,644 --> 01:11:13,909
Yeah, well, I guess
that's Emerson's way of...

1179
01:11:13,981 --> 01:11:15,471
finding the bright side.

1180
01:11:15,549 --> 01:11:18,040
You know Emerson, sir?

1181
01:11:18,118 --> 01:11:19,779
I know some.

1182
01:11:23,590 --> 01:11:26,024
So where are you from,
Captain?

1183
01:11:26,093 --> 01:11:28,185
What'd you do
before the war?

1184
01:11:29,730 --> 01:11:31,698
What's the pool up to?

1185
01:11:35,535 --> 01:11:39,301
You know, I think
it's around 300, sir.

1186
01:11:39,373 --> 01:11:41,739
Well,
when it gets up to 500,

1187
01:11:41,808 --> 01:11:44,208
I'll give you the answers
and we'll split the money.

1188
01:11:44,278 --> 01:11:46,211
How about that?

1189
01:11:46,279 --> 01:11:48,009
Well, if that's
the way you feel, sir,

1190
01:11:48,081 --> 01:11:50,072
I feel it's my duty
under your command

1191
01:11:50,150 --> 01:11:51,481
to suggest that we wait

1192
01:11:51,551 --> 01:11:54,145
until it gets up
to a thousand, sir.

1193
01:11:56,123 --> 01:11:58,387
What if we don't
live that long?

1194
01:12:01,161 --> 01:12:02,185
500?

1195
01:12:02,262 --> 01:12:04,753
500 would be good,
yeah.

1196
01:12:04,831 --> 01:12:05,797
Yes, sir.

1197
01:12:05,865 --> 01:12:07,163
Yeah.

1198
01:12:09,469 --> 01:12:11,096
Get some sleep,
Corporal.

1199
01:12:11,171 --> 01:12:12,331
Yes, sir.

1200
01:13:18,638 --> 01:13:20,230
<b><font color="#404040">SOLDIER:</font></b>
Who's got sulfa powder?

1201
01:13:23,343 --> 01:13:25,811
<b><font color="#404040">SOLDIER:</font></b> Medic!
My buddy's bleeding!

1202
01:13:25,879 --> 01:13:27,312
He needs a tourniquet!

1203
01:13:27,381 --> 01:13:28,313
WADE.

1204
01:13:28,382 --> 01:13:29,406
<b><font color="#404040">WADE:</font></b> Yes, sir?

1205
01:13:29,483 --> 01:13:30,814
See what you can do.

1206
01:13:30,884 --> 01:13:31,816
Yes, sir.

1207
01:13:31,885 --> 01:13:32,977
Hold on, fellas.

1208
01:13:33,053 --> 01:13:34,520
It won't be
much longer.

1209
01:13:34,588 --> 01:13:36,021
How we doing here?

1210
01:13:37,290 --> 01:13:38,621
All right.

1211
01:13:38,692 --> 01:13:41,160
Yeah, doing all right.
Don't worry about it.

1212
01:13:41,228 --> 01:13:43,196
Doc's in town.

1213
01:13:43,263 --> 01:13:44,594
<b><font color="#404040">JACKSON:</font></b> It's all right.
It's all right.

1214
01:13:44,664 --> 01:13:46,097
Don't worry, fellas.

1215
01:13:46,166 --> 01:13:47,394
The 29th Infantry's
breaking through.

1216
01:13:47,467 --> 01:13:48,593
They'll be here soon.

1217
01:13:48,668 --> 01:13:51,136
<b><font color="#404040">SOLDIER:</font></b> Plasma.
Anybody got plasma?

1218
01:13:51,204 --> 01:13:53,229
Captain.
Hey, Captain.

1219
01:13:53,306 --> 01:13:54,967
Soldier,
you want to fill me in?

1220
01:13:55,042 --> 01:13:57,010
Uh, yeah.
Lieutenant Dewindt, sir.

1221
01:13:57,077 --> 01:13:58,339
99th Troop Carrier Squadron

1222
01:13:58,412 --> 01:14:00,937
carrying in
327th Glider Infantry.

1223
01:14:01,014 --> 01:14:02,447
This one was mine, sir.

1224
01:14:02,516 --> 01:14:03,847
I was the pilot.

1225
01:14:03,917 --> 01:14:04,906
22 men dead.

1226
01:14:04,985 --> 01:14:06,919
I ended up over there
without a scratch.

1227
01:14:06,987 --> 01:14:08,284
It took my copilot's head
right off.

1228
01:14:08,355 --> 01:14:10,220
Well, where's the unit?
Who are these people?

1229
01:14:10,290 --> 01:14:12,155
Well, the guys
we came in with, sir,

1230
01:14:12,225 --> 01:14:14,625
they headed off first night.
Haven't seen them since.

1231
01:14:14,694 --> 01:14:16,889
Meantime, other guys
keep showing up,

1232
01:14:16,963 --> 01:14:18,726
1, 2, half-dozen
at a time.

1233
01:14:18,800 --> 01:14:21,768
Then some officer'll come along
and patch together a mixed unit,

1234
01:14:21,835 --> 01:14:24,269
head off to make trouble, sir.

1235
01:14:24,337 --> 01:14:26,237
We're looking for
a Private James Ryan.

1236
01:14:26,306 --> 01:14:28,604
He was in Baker Company
5-0-6 of the 101st.

1237
01:14:28,675 --> 01:14:29,903
No, you got me, sir.

1238
01:14:29,976 --> 01:14:31,341
A lot of guys
come in and out of here.

1239
01:14:31,411 --> 01:14:32,537
- Upham.
- Yes, sir?

1240
01:14:32,612 --> 01:14:35,547
Check out that squad.
See if Ryan's in it.

1241
01:14:35,615 --> 01:14:37,446
Yes, sir.

1242
01:14:37,517 --> 01:14:38,609
REIBEN.

1243
01:14:38,685 --> 01:14:40,880
Smell that leg
right there.

1244
01:14:40,954 --> 01:14:43,013
Find out if it's
south of cheese.

1245
01:14:48,028 --> 01:14:49,325
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(SNIFFS)</font></b>
Phew.

1246
01:14:49,396 --> 01:14:50,454
<b><font color="#404040">WADE:</font></b> What?

1247
01:14:52,065 --> 01:14:53,327
Juden.

1248
01:14:55,135 --> 01:14:56,067
Juden.

1249
01:14:56,136 --> 01:14:58,502
<b><font color="#404040">SOLDIER:</font></b> Keep moving.
Keep moving!

1250
01:14:58,572 --> 01:15:00,130
Juden.

1251
01:15:00,207 --> 01:15:02,505
I'm Juden,
you know?

1252
01:15:02,576 --> 01:15:04,840
Ju-den.

1253
01:15:04,911 --> 01:15:06,503
Yeah, I couldn't
pry him out of there

1254
01:15:06,580 --> 01:15:08,013
hard as I tried.

1255
01:15:08,081 --> 01:15:09,343
I'd need a winch.

1256
01:15:09,416 --> 01:15:10,405
<b><font color="#404040">HORVATH:</font></b> Yeah.

1257
01:15:13,887 --> 01:15:14,911
<b><font color="#404040">HORVATH:</font></b> Stars.

1258
01:15:14,988 --> 01:15:18,219
Yep,
Brigadier General Amend,

1259
01:15:18,291 --> 01:15:20,953
deputy commander, 101st.

1260
01:15:21,027 --> 01:15:23,552
Some fucking genius
had the great idea

1261
01:15:23,630 --> 01:15:25,063
of welding a couple
of steel plates

1262
01:15:25,132 --> 01:15:27,100
onto our deck to keep
the general safe

1263
01:15:27,167 --> 01:15:28,566
from ground fire.

1264
01:15:28,635 --> 01:15:30,330
Unfortunately, they forgot
to tell me about it

1265
01:15:30,403 --> 01:15:32,564
until we were just
getting airborne.

1266
01:15:32,639 --> 01:15:34,665
Well, that's like trying
to fly a freight train.

1267
01:15:34,742 --> 01:15:36,003
OK?

1268
01:15:36,076 --> 01:15:37,338
Gross overload.

1269
01:15:37,410 --> 01:15:40,174
Trim characteristics
all shot to hell.

1270
01:15:40,247 --> 01:15:43,239
I nearly broke both my arms
trying to keep her level.

1271
01:15:43,316 --> 01:15:45,511
And when--
And when we released,

1272
01:15:45,585 --> 01:15:47,746
you know, I cut
as hard as I could,

1273
01:15:47,821 --> 01:15:49,345
tried to gain
some altitude

1274
01:15:49,422 --> 01:15:51,356
and still keep her
from stalling.

1275
01:15:51,424 --> 01:15:53,416
We came down
like a fucking meteor.

1276
01:15:53,494 --> 01:15:56,326
And this is how
we ended up.

1277
01:15:56,396 --> 01:15:58,455
And the others,

1278
01:15:58,532 --> 01:16:01,160
they stopped easy enough
OK, though, you know?

1279
01:16:01,234 --> 01:16:03,964
We were just--
We were just too damn heavy,

1280
01:16:04,037 --> 01:16:05,197
you know?

1281
01:16:05,272 --> 01:16:07,536
The grass was wet.

1282
01:16:07,607 --> 01:16:10,041
Downward slope and all.

1283
01:16:10,110 --> 01:16:12,875
22 guys dead.

1284
01:16:14,981 --> 01:16:16,881
All that for a general?

1285
01:16:16,950 --> 01:16:19,111
One man.

1286
01:16:20,854 --> 01:16:22,481
Lot of that going around.

1287
01:16:22,556 --> 01:16:24,114
FUBAR.

1288
01:16:24,191 --> 01:16:25,556
FUBAR.

1289
01:16:25,625 --> 01:16:26,990
FUBAR.

1290
01:16:27,060 --> 01:16:28,391
FUBAR.

1291
01:16:28,461 --> 01:16:30,588
Y'all got that right.

1292
01:16:30,664 --> 01:16:33,326
I looked up "FUBAR" in
the German dictionary.

1293
01:16:33,400 --> 01:16:34,992
There's no "FUBAR"
in there.

1294
01:16:35,068 --> 01:16:36,092
- Upham.
- Yes, sir?

1295
01:16:36,169 --> 01:16:37,659
There's more paratroops
out there.

1296
01:16:37,737 --> 01:16:38,863
Find out
if one of them's Ryan.

1297
01:16:38,939 --> 01:16:39,963
Yes, sir.

1298
01:16:40,040 --> 01:16:43,100
Oh, you might want to
check these out, sir.

1299
01:16:43,176 --> 01:16:44,939
Dog tags.

1300
01:16:45,011 --> 01:16:47,605
More than I really
want to count, sir.

1301
01:16:48,748 --> 01:16:51,741
I've-- I've covered
a lot of bodies, sir.

1302
01:16:51,819 --> 01:16:53,877
<b><font color="#404040">MILLER:</font></b> JACKSON...

1303
01:16:53,954 --> 01:16:55,512
start going
through those.

1304
01:16:55,589 --> 01:16:56,647
Yes, sir.

1305
01:16:58,058 --> 01:16:59,958
I'll help.

1306
01:17:01,461 --> 01:17:03,053
What do you think,
JACKSON?

1307
01:17:03,129 --> 01:17:04,323
Do you think that
little prick's in there?

1308
01:17:04,397 --> 01:17:06,331
Well, if he is,
I'm gonna find him.

1309
01:17:06,399 --> 01:17:07,696
I bet that
son of a bitch is.

1310
01:17:07,767 --> 01:17:09,326
<b><font color="#404040">REIBEN:</font></b> I got big money saying
this guy's still alive.

1311
01:17:09,403 --> 01:17:11,632
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b> 10 bucks
says I nail him first.

1312
01:17:11,705 --> 01:17:13,195
Let's see
who we got in here.

1313
01:17:13,273 --> 01:17:14,604
You mugs don't
stand a chance.

1314
01:17:14,674 --> 01:17:16,403
All right, you think this little
shit bird's in here or what?

1315
01:17:16,476 --> 01:17:18,273
Just keep looking.

1316
01:17:18,345 --> 01:17:20,779
All right.
Gary lanico.

1317
01:17:20,847 --> 01:17:22,212
Ben Rubino.
Mike Cessacchio.

1318
01:17:22,282 --> 01:17:24,477
I swear, all the guineas
are buying it, huh?

1319
01:17:24,551 --> 01:17:26,883
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b> Oh, come on,
not the right name.

1320
01:17:26,953 --> 01:17:29,149
Wee Willie Winkie,
that's a buddy of yours.

1321
01:17:29,223 --> 01:17:31,417
<b><font color="#404040">REIBEN:</font></b>
We gotta find this prick.

1322
01:17:35,729 --> 01:17:38,061
Where is
this son of a bitch?

1323
01:17:38,131 --> 01:17:39,792
Don't mix them up,
JACKSON, all right?

1324
01:17:39,866 --> 01:17:40,833
Keep them in your
own fucking pile.

1325
01:17:40,900 --> 01:17:43,266
How am I supposed
to know who we got?

1326
01:17:43,336 --> 01:17:46,134
Why don't you just shut up,
REIBEN, all right?

1327
01:17:46,206 --> 01:17:47,469
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b>
Everybody be friends.

1328
01:17:47,541 --> 01:17:49,168
<b><font color="#404040">REIBEN:</font></b>
Cranky there, huh?

1329
01:17:50,577 --> 01:17:51,874
I think
I got a winner.

1330
01:17:51,945 --> 01:17:53,435
What are you
talking about?

1331
01:17:53,513 --> 01:17:54,980
Ryan.

1332
01:17:55,048 --> 01:17:56,072
Ryan?

1333
01:17:56,149 --> 01:17:58,049
Take a look at that,
MELLISH.

1334
01:17:58,118 --> 01:17:59,745
You know what? You're a genius.
You really are.

1335
01:17:59,819 --> 01:18:01,650
R-I-E-N-N-E.

1336
01:18:01,721 --> 01:18:03,655
That's Rienne.
And that's French, all right?

1337
01:18:03,723 --> 01:18:05,190
You know what that means?

1338
01:18:05,258 --> 01:18:06,521
<b><font color="#404040">JACKSON:</font></b>
It's means nothing.

1339
01:18:06,594 --> 01:18:07,993
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b>
What beats 3 of a kind?

1340
01:18:08,062 --> 01:18:09,426
<b><font color="#404040">JACKSON:</font></b>
I got shit here.

1341
01:18:09,496 --> 01:18:10,986
I got all guys
from New York.

1342
01:18:11,064 --> 01:18:12,497
<b><font color="#404040">REIBEN:</font></b> Do you need
a hand with that?

1343
01:18:12,565 --> 01:18:13,998
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b> Ah,
I got a full house.

1344
01:18:14,067 --> 01:18:16,092
<b><font color="#404040">REIBEN:</font></b> Got you beat.
Straight flush.

1345
01:18:16,169 --> 01:18:18,137
You were looking
at my tags.

1346
01:18:18,204 --> 01:18:19,501
You're cheating.
You know?

1347
01:18:19,572 --> 01:18:20,664
Ryan.

1348
01:18:20,740 --> 01:18:22,401
<b><font color="#404040">REIBEN:</font></b> Fuckin' unreal,
this guy.

1349
01:18:22,475 --> 01:18:23,874
Do you need a hand
with that?

1350
01:18:23,943 --> 01:18:25,206
Can you read that shit?

1351
01:18:25,279 --> 01:18:27,679
Jesus Christ, look at
this poor bastard, huh?

1352
01:18:27,748 --> 01:18:29,578
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b> I guess they're
not bulletproof, huh?

1353
01:18:29,649 --> 01:18:30,877
<b><font color="#404040">REIBEN:</font></b> Guess not.
All right?

1354
01:18:30,950 --> 01:18:32,440
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b> I don't like what
he's got between his ears.

1355
01:18:32,519 --> 01:18:34,749
<b><font color="#404040">JACKSON:</font></b> Sort of
what you fellas got

1356
01:18:34,821 --> 01:18:36,049
between your legs.

1357
01:18:36,122 --> 01:18:38,556
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b>
We got to give him that.

1358
01:18:38,625 --> 01:18:39,751
Not bad for you,
JACKSON.

1359
01:18:39,826 --> 01:18:41,316
I got 3 of a kind.

1360
01:18:41,394 --> 01:18:42,486
Full house.

1361
01:18:42,562 --> 01:18:44,895
The whole goddamn
airborne's watching.

1362
01:18:44,965 --> 01:18:46,227
These aren't poker chips.

1363
01:18:46,300 --> 01:18:47,561
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b>
All right, all right.

1364
01:18:47,634 --> 01:18:49,568
<b><font color="#404040">WADE:</font></b>
Put 'em back in there!

1365
01:19:13,827 --> 01:19:15,522
He's not here.

1366
01:19:18,298 --> 01:19:19,560
<b><font color="#404040">WADE:</font></b> Put 'em back.

1367
01:19:19,632 --> 01:19:20,929
Maybe we should bust up

1368
01:19:21,000 --> 01:19:22,491
into a couple of
different groups, huh?

1369
01:19:22,570 --> 01:19:24,060
And wander the woods
like Hansel and Gretel,

1370
01:19:24,138 --> 01:19:25,162
calling his name.

1371
01:19:25,239 --> 01:19:26,865
He's bound to hear us
sooner or later.

1372
01:19:26,940 --> 01:19:28,407
Ryan!

1373
01:19:28,475 --> 01:19:31,672
That might be a little
hard to do, Captain.

1374
01:19:31,745 --> 01:19:33,235
Maybe the locals
have seen him.

1375
01:19:33,313 --> 01:19:34,905
Hey, you know--
uh, excusez-moi.

1376
01:19:34,981 --> 01:19:36,949
Parlez-vous Ryan,
James ryan?

1377
01:19:37,016 --> 01:19:38,677
Merci. Merci beaucoup.

1378
01:19:38,752 --> 01:19:40,744
Ryan! Anybody know Ryan,
101st Airborne?

1379
01:19:40,821 --> 01:19:43,085
Ryan? You know
a guy named Ryan?

1380
01:19:43,157 --> 01:19:44,920
Private James Ryan
from lowa?

1381
01:19:44,991 --> 01:19:47,721
Anybody know a Ryan?

1382
01:19:47,794 --> 01:19:48,886
James Ryan?!

1383
01:19:48,962 --> 01:19:51,522
Hey, Joe,

1384
01:19:51,598 --> 01:19:53,190
doesn't, uh, Michaelson

1385
01:19:53,266 --> 01:19:55,826
pal around with a Ryan
from "C" Company?

1386
01:19:55,902 --> 01:19:57,096
Yeah, I think so.

1387
01:19:57,170 --> 01:19:59,264
Well, bring him
up here, would you?

1388
01:20:08,281 --> 01:20:09,543
You know
Private Ryan?

1389
01:20:09,616 --> 01:20:11,015
You're gonna have
to speak up, sir.

1390
01:20:11,084 --> 01:20:12,381
You're gonna have
to speak up, sir!

1391
01:20:12,452 --> 01:20:14,113
My hearing
is not so good!

1392
01:20:14,187 --> 01:20:15,279
It comes and goes!

1393
01:20:15,355 --> 01:20:17,380
A German grenade went off
right by my head!

1394
01:20:17,457 --> 01:20:18,550
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(LOUDER)</font></b>
Got it, got it.

1395
01:20:18,626 --> 01:20:20,594
Do you know
Private Ryan?

1396
01:20:20,661 --> 01:20:22,094
Who?

1397
01:20:22,163 --> 01:20:24,528
Private Ryan?
James Ryan?

1398
01:20:24,597 --> 01:20:25,859
Jimmy Ryan?

1399
01:20:25,932 --> 01:20:28,924
James.
James Francis Ryan.

1400
01:20:29,002 --> 01:20:31,835
No, no, no.
James Francis Ryan.

1401
01:20:31,905 --> 01:20:34,897
Get me a pencil.
Something to write on.

1402
01:20:34,974 --> 01:20:36,966
Quick! Quick!
Come on, a pencil!

1403
01:20:39,180 --> 01:20:41,080
Here you are.
A small one, sir.

1404
01:20:41,148 --> 01:20:43,115
Write this down.

1405
01:20:43,183 --> 01:20:45,151
James Francis Ryan,
Question mark.

1406
01:20:45,218 --> 01:20:47,448
Iowa, question mark.

1407
01:20:47,520 --> 01:20:49,613
Do you know him?
Does he know him?

1408
01:20:49,689 --> 01:20:50,951
Read the message. Look.

1409
01:20:53,593 --> 01:20:55,687
Yeah. Of course
I know him, sir.

1410
01:20:55,763 --> 01:20:57,355
Does he know
where he is?

1411
01:21:00,734 --> 01:21:02,200
Yeah, yeah.

1412
01:21:02,268 --> 01:21:04,793
<b><font color="#404040">MICHAELSON:</font></b> We missed our drop zone
by about 20 miles,

1413
01:21:04,871 --> 01:21:08,170
ended up way over by
Bumville or some damn place.

1414
01:21:08,241 --> 01:21:09,572
Him, me, and a couple
of other guys

1415
01:21:09,642 --> 01:21:11,337
were coming here
to the rally point,

1416
01:21:11,411 --> 01:21:14,039
ran into a colonel
who was gathering up men

1417
01:21:14,113 --> 01:21:17,242
to go to, uh... Ramelle...

1418
01:21:17,318 --> 01:21:18,250
Ramelle.

1419
01:21:18,319 --> 01:21:19,513
To baby-sit a bridge.

1420
01:21:19,587 --> 01:21:20,848
That's the last
I've seen of him, sir.

1421
01:21:20,920 --> 01:21:22,683
Great! Great!
Thank-- Thank you.

1422
01:21:22,755 --> 01:21:24,780
<b><font color="#404040">MILLER:</font></b> Write thank you.
Read and thank you.

1423
01:21:24,858 --> 01:21:26,086
<b><font color="#404040">MICHAELSON:</font></b>
You're welcome!

1424
01:21:26,159 --> 01:21:27,421
Assemble on me.

1425
01:21:29,629 --> 01:21:31,256
Thank you, Lieutenant.

1426
01:21:34,368 --> 01:21:36,563
Ramelle.

1427
01:21:36,637 --> 01:21:39,969
We're here. There.

1428
01:21:40,039 --> 01:21:41,233
Ramelle...

1429
01:21:41,307 --> 01:21:43,241
is on the Merderet River
right here,

1430
01:21:43,309 --> 01:21:45,243
just to the southwest
of us.

1431
01:21:45,311 --> 01:21:47,245
You know anything
about this bridge

1432
01:21:47,313 --> 01:21:48,905
he was talking
about, Captain?

1433
01:21:48,982 --> 01:21:52,441
Yep. The target has
always been Cherbourg.

1434
01:21:52,520 --> 01:21:55,978
We can't push on Paris until
we take a deep water port,

1435
01:21:56,056 --> 01:21:57,853
and Rommel knows that.

1436
01:21:57,925 --> 01:21:59,186
So he's gonna try
to get his armor

1437
01:21:59,259 --> 01:22:02,422
across the Merderet River
anywhere he can.

1438
01:22:02,495 --> 01:22:05,123
That way, he can hit
our invasion forces in the flank

1439
01:22:05,198 --> 01:22:07,462
when we make the big
right turn to Cherbourg.

1440
01:22:07,534 --> 01:22:09,593
That makes any village
on that river

1441
01:22:09,669 --> 01:22:12,434
with an intact bridge
solid gold real estate.

1442
01:22:15,009 --> 01:22:17,671
<b><font color="#DF01D7">(COMPASS RATTLING)</font></b>

1443
01:22:32,693 --> 01:22:34,718
Let's go.

1444
01:22:43,570 --> 01:22:45,333
<b><font color="#404040">WADE:</font></b> Captain.

1445
01:23:23,443 --> 01:23:25,308
<b><font color="#404040">HORVATH:</font></b>
What the hell is that?

1446
01:23:26,947 --> 01:23:28,539
<b><font color="#404040">MILLER:</font></b> A radar site.

1447
01:23:28,616 --> 01:23:30,311
It's got to be
out of action.

1448
01:23:30,384 --> 01:23:32,443
Well, it looks like we
got something in that...

1449
01:23:32,519 --> 01:23:35,078
sandbag bunker
right under the station.

1450
01:23:36,155 --> 01:23:37,179
See it?

1451
01:23:37,256 --> 01:23:39,121
Yeah.
That's my guess, too.

1452
01:23:40,727 --> 01:23:42,991
What is it?

1453
01:23:43,062 --> 01:23:45,462
Machine gun.
Probably MG-42.

1454
01:23:45,532 --> 01:23:47,796
Jesus. Is that
what got those guys?

1455
01:23:47,868 --> 01:23:49,836
Maybe one of them's
our boy.

1456
01:23:49,903 --> 01:23:51,564
<b><font color="#404040">MILLER:</font></b> No, their
patches are 82nd,

1457
01:23:51,639 --> 01:23:52,970
so your luck's
not that good.

1458
01:23:53,040 --> 01:23:55,530
I don't know how fast
the rest of you Betties are,

1459
01:23:55,608 --> 01:23:58,008
but I'm thinking we detour
this way quick and quiet,

1460
01:23:58,077 --> 01:23:59,806
the krauts will never
even know we were here.

1461
01:23:59,879 --> 01:24:02,643
So, Captain, what I'm
trying to say is,

1462
01:24:02,715 --> 01:24:04,843
why don't we just
go around the thing?

1463
01:24:04,918 --> 01:24:06,715
I hear what
you're saying,

1464
01:24:06,787 --> 01:24:08,721
but we can't
go around it.

1465
01:24:08,789 --> 01:24:11,849
I'm with Reiben
on this one, sir.

1466
01:24:11,925 --> 01:24:13,858
I mean,
we left them 88s.

1467
01:24:13,926 --> 01:24:15,188
For the air force.

1468
01:24:15,261 --> 01:24:17,661
The air force isn't
gonna spend ordinance

1469
01:24:17,730 --> 01:24:19,755
on one machine gun.

1470
01:24:19,832 --> 01:24:22,027
<b><font color="#404040">MELLISH:</font></b> Uh, Captain.

1471
01:24:22,101 --> 01:24:25,037
We can still skip it and
accomplish our mission.

1472
01:24:25,105 --> 01:24:27,733
I mean, this isn't
our mission, right, sir?

1473
01:24:27,808 --> 01:24:30,003
Oh, that's what you
want to do, Mellish?

1474
01:24:30,077 --> 01:24:31,271
You just want
to leave it here

1475
01:24:31,345 --> 01:24:33,437
so they can ambush the next
company that comes along?

1476
01:24:33,513 --> 01:24:35,481
No, sir, that's not
what I'm saying.

1477
01:24:35,548 --> 01:24:38,142
I'm simply saying, it seems
like an unnecessary risk

1478
01:24:38,217 --> 01:24:39,479
given our objective, sir.

1479
01:24:39,552 --> 01:24:41,679
Our objective
is to win the war.

1480
01:24:44,658 --> 01:24:46,626
Sir, I just, uh,

1481
01:24:46,694 --> 01:24:49,162
I don't have a good feeling
about this one.

1482
01:24:50,664 --> 01:24:52,631
Well, when was
the last time

1483
01:24:52,699 --> 01:24:54,326
you felt good
about anything?

1484
01:25:14,921 --> 01:25:19,119
All right, 3 runners
with suppressing fire.

1485
01:25:19,192 --> 01:25:21,161
Mellish,
you hook to the right.

